ODE XXI

WRITTEN in anticipation of entertaining M. Valerius Messalla Corvinus. Dillr. bids us compare with this Ode Epp. 1. 5.

‘Jar of Massic, as old as myself, your potent contents were kept for some happy occasion, and they shall be broached to-day for Corvinus. He, philosopher as he is, will not despise you. Old Cato, they tell us, did not object to a cup of wine. You make genius flow3 you give fresh hope to the anxious and courage to the poor. With your help, and Liber and Venus and the Graces, we will keep the banquet up till daylight.’
